    <etym xml:lang="ru">Этимологически и по образованию сближаем с <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>pīšānī</w><gloss><q>лоб</q></gloss></mentioned> (= „выступающая часть“).
        Оба слова заключают <mentioned xml:lang="x-oldirn"
                ><lang/><w>patiš-</w><gloss><q>против</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
            xml:lang="x-oldirn"><w/><gloss><q>впереди</q></gloss></mentioned>, ; %ifesun%i ←
        %ipaitiš%i + %iuna%i. Н. %sPetersson%s, предполагая исходное значение ‘острый’, ‘колоть’ и
        т. п., возводит %ifis(yn)%i к <mentioned xml:lang="ine"
                    ><lang/><w>*peik-</w><gloss><q>колоть</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
            xml:lang="ine"><w/><gloss><q>чертить</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"
                    ><w/><gloss><q>писать</q></gloss></mentioned>, (ос. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_fyssyn"/>). Эта этимология с семантической стороны кажется нам очень
                натянутой.%n<bibl><author>Petersson</author><ref target="#ref_LUÅ"/><biblScope
                xml:lang="ru">1920 XVI 3 63 сл</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">1920 XVI 3 63
                ff</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">It is related to <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                    ><lang/><w>pīšānī</w><gloss><q>forehead</q></gloss></mentioned> (= “prominent
        part”) etymologically and derivationally. Both words contain <mentioned xml:lang="x-oldirn"
                ><lang/><w>patiš-</w><gloss><q>opposite</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned
            xml:lang="x-oldirn"><w/><gloss><q>ahead</q></gloss></mentioned>, ; %ifesun%i ←
        %ipaitiš%i + %iuna%i. Н. %sPetersson%s, assuming the initial meaning ‘sharp’, ‘stab’, etc.,
        traces %ifis(yn)%i back to <mentioned xml:lang="ine"
                ><lang/><w>*peik-</w><gloss><q>stab</q></gloss></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="ine"
                    ><w/><gloss><q>draw</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"
                    ><w/><gloss><q>write</q></gloss></mentioned>, (Ossetic <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_fyssyn"/>). This etymology from the semantic point of view seems to us
        very forced.%n<bibl><author>Petersson</author><ref target="#ref_LUÅ"/><biblScope
                xml:lang="ru">1920 XVI 3 63 сл</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">1920 XVI 3
                63ff</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
